.TH "Tofrodos" "1" "16 March 2026" "Tofrodos 2.0.0"
.SH NAME
Tofrodos \- convert text files between DOS and Unix formats.
.SH SYNOPSIS
\f[B]fromdos\f[R] [\f[I]options\f[R]] [\f[I]file\&...\f[R]]
.PD 0
.P
.PD
\f[B]todos\f[R] [\f[I]options\f[R]] [\f[I]file\&...\f[R]]
.SH DESCRIPTION
DOS (and Windows) plain ASCII or Unicode UTF\-8 text files traditionally
have a carriage return and line feed pair to mark the end of each line,
while Unix\-type systems (including Linux, macOS, FreeBSD, etc) use a
line feed for that purpose.
.PP
\f[B]fromdos\f[R] converts such files from the DOS format to the Unix
format, while \f[B]todos\f[R] converts them in the other direction.
.PP
The programs accept multiple filenames and wildcards as their arguments.
You can also use them in a pipe.
If the program finds its input redirected, it will take its input from
stdin and send its output to stdout.
.PP
Note that \f[B]fromdos\f[R] and \f[B]todos\f[R] are actually the same
program.
The name under which the program is run determines the default direction
it converts (unless overridden by an option).
If you prefer, you can also rename it to \f[B]unix2dos\f[R] (which will
make it behave like \f[B]todos\f[R]) and \f[B]dos2unix\f[R] (which will
make it act as though it is \f[B]fromdos\f[R]).
.SH OPTIONS
.TP
\f[B]\-b, \-\-backup\f[R]
Make a backup of the original file.
It will have a \(lq.bak\(rq suffix appended to its name.
For example, \(lqfilename.ext\(rq becomes \(lqfilename.ext.bak\(rq, and
if there is already a file named \(lqfilename.ext.bak\(rq in that same
directory, it will be silently replaced.
Note: the program behaves differently if it is compiled for DOS (as
compared to being compiled for Linux, Windows, macOS, FreeBSD or other
systems).
In view of the filename restrictions present on that system, where files
have at most a single extension, the original file extension (if any)
will be replaced by \(lq.bak\(rq.
For example, \(lqfilename.ext\(rq becomes \(lqfilename.bak\(rq.
.TP
\f[B]\-d, \-\-dos2unix, \-\-fromdos\f[R]
Convert from DOS to Unix.
This forces the program to convert the file in the specified direction.
By default, if the program is named \f[B]fromdos\f[R] or
\f[B]dos2unix\f[R], it will convert files to a Unix format.
If it is named \f[B]todos\f[R] or \f[B]unix2dos\f[R], it will them to a
DOS format.
Using the \(lq\-\-fromdos\(rq option forces the program to convert to a
Unix format regardless of the program name.
Likewise, using the \(lq\-\-todos\(rq option forces it to convert to a
DOS format.
.TP
\f[B]\-e, \-\-exit\-on\-error\f[R]
Abort processing the rest of the files if there is an error in any file.
Normally, the program will simply skip to process the next file on the
command line when it encounters an error.
This option causes it to abort instead.
.TP
\f[B]\-f, \-\-force\f[R]
Convert the file even if it is not writeable (that is, it is
read\-only).
By default, if the program finds that the file does not have write
permission, it will not process it.
This option forces the conversion even if it is read\-only.
.TP
\f[B]\-h, \-\-help\f[R]
Display a short help screen on the program usage and quit.
.TP
\f[B]\-l <logfile>, \-\-log=<logfile>\f[R]
Log most error messages and all verbose messages to <logfile>.
Note though that if your command line has an error, such as when you
specify an option that the program does not recognize, the error message
will still be printed on stderr (which usually means the screen), and
not logged, since at the time the program checks the command line, it
has still not set up the log file.
.TP
\f[B]\-o, \-\-overwrite\f[R]
Overwrite the original file (no backup).
This is the default.
.TP
\f[B]\-p, \-\-preserve\f[R]
Preserve file ownership and time on Unix\-type systems (like Linux,
macOS, FreeBSD, etc).
On Windows and MSDOS, it only preserves the file time.
Note that on Unix\-type systems, the ownership will only be preserved if
the program is run as root or via \f[B]sudo\f[R], otherwise it will just
set the file time and silently fail the change of ownership.
If you want a warning message when the file ownership cannot be changed,
set the verbose mode as well, using the \(lq\-\-verbose\(rq option.
.TP
\f[B]\-u, \-\-unix2dos, \-\-todos\f[R]
Convert from Unix to DOS.
See the \(lq\-\-fromdos\(rq option above for more information.
.TP
\f[B]\-v, \-\-verbose\f[R]
Display the current version and quit.
.SH EXIT CODE
Tofrodos terminates with an exit code of 0 on success and 1 on error.
.PP
If the program is invoked with multiple files on the command line, the
default behaviour is to skip to the next file in the list if an error is
encountered with any file.
In such a case, the exit code returned will the status of the last file
processed (ie, 0 on success, 1 on failure).
If this is not desirable, use the \(lq\-\-exit\-on\-error\(rq option,
which will force the program to abort immediately with the appropriate
exit code on encountering an error.
.SH EXAMPLES
To convert a single file to Unix format (with line feeds):
.IP
.EX
fromdos filetoconvert.txt
.EE
.PP
To convert multiple files, including wildcard characters, to DOS format
(with carriage return/line feed pairs):
.IP
.EX
todos readme.txt manual.html *.c *.h
.EE
.PP
If you want the original file backed up with a \(lq.bak\(rq extension:
.IP
.EX
todos \-\-backup filetoconvert.txt
.EE
.PP
To use the program in a pipe:
.IP
.EX
cat dosversion.txt | fromdos | diff \- unixversion.txt
.EE
